{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523316"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:54:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:54:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13891"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13891"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.17,0.32,0.28,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75841"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6510"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13891"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61354"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"2466"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14076"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75841"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 77-year-old woman presents to the GP clinic with multiple purple-brown lumps on her lower legs. The spots first showed up 20 years ago and have gradually increased in number. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She was born in Greece and moved to Australia 40 years ago. On examination, she looks well with vital signs within normal limits. There are multiple non-tender, firm, purple-brown lumps on both lower legs, ranging from 0.5-3 cm across. The spots don\u0027t blanch when pressed. There are no swollen lymph nodes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how this condition develops?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bacterial infection of skin blood vessels","Autoimmune destruction of melanocytes","Malignant transformation of Langerhans cells","Uncontrolled growth of plasma cells","Viral-induced blood vessel cell growth"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic (sporadic) Kaposi sarcoma, which typically shows up in older people from Mediterranean or Eastern European backgrounds. The key features are slowly progressive, non-blanching, purple-brown lumps that mainly affect the legs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral-induced blood vessel cell growth\u003C/strong\u003E is spot on for how this condition develops. Human herpesvirus 8 (HHV-8), also called Kaposi sarcoma herpesvirus, infects the cells lining blood vessels and makes them grow out of control. The virus makes proteins that promote new blood vessel growth and inflammation while stopping cell death. But catching HHV-8 isn\u0027t enough on its own to cause Kaposi sarcoma - other factors like a weakened immune system or genetic makeup play a part too.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune destruction of melanocytes\u003C/strong\u003E is what happens in vitiligo, where you get patches of skin losing their colour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalignant transformation of Langerhans cells\u003C/strong\u003E is what you see in Langerhans cell histiocytosis, which usually shows up as scaly, red patches or bumps and can affect multiple parts of the body.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUncontrolled growth of plasma cells\u003C/strong\u003E happens in conditions like multiple myeloma or skin plasmacytoma, which look different and don\u0027t usually cause purple-brown lumps.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial infection of skin blood vessels\u003C/strong\u003E would cause acute inflammation and infection, not the long, slow progression we\u0027re seeing here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are four types of Kaposi sarcoma: classic (sporadic), endemic (African), iatrogenic (in transplant patients), and epidemic (in people with AIDS). The classic type, which this patient has, progresses the slowest and has the best outlook. All types are linked to HHV-8 infection, but how weak the immune system is and genetic factors influence how it presents and progresses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Classic (sporadic) Kaposi sarcoma typically affects elderly people of Mediterranean or Eastern European descent","Classic Kaposi sarcoma has a slow-going course that progresses over many years","Human herpesvirus 8 (HHV-8) infection is needed but not enough on its own to cause Kaposi sarcoma"],"references":["Cesarman E, Damania B, Krown SE, Martin J, Bower M, Whitby D. Kaposi sarcoma. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2019 Jan 31;5(1):1\u201321."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61354"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13891"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20829"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20829"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/VhB7Vyh6jnyuEoyiryp0LZ8KRlhVSc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/VhB7Vyh6jnyuEoyiryp0LZ8KRlhVSc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61354"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-31T23:17:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T23:19:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6510"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"758